ly optional, and Jews in turn created spaces and programs to meet new social needs. The contexts of Jewish life expanded beyond the confines of "traditional" Jewish spaces into sites of consumption and leisure, sometimes to the consternation of Jewish authorities. Sarah Wobick-Segev argues that the social practices that developed between 1890 and the 1930s-such as celebrating holydays at hotels and restaurants, or sending children to summer camp-fundamentally reshaped Jewish community, redefining and extending the boundaries of where Jewishness happened.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCommunity lifezEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aIndividualismzEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aJewszEuropexSocial life and customsy20th century. 0aJudaism and secularismzEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aLeisurezEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aPublic spaceszEuropexHistoryy20th century. 4aJewish holidays. 4aJewish life. 4aModern Jewish history. 4achildren. 4aemotions. 4agender studies. 4amodern European history. 4areligious studies. 4aspace. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503606548zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503606548423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503606548.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles